      {
        "id": 2903064,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-06-01T13:26:57.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"10\" data-topic=\"161478\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Almost like a cross between Ramonet and PYCM.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>For me, with the usual caveat that \u201ccomparisons are odious\u201d, a PYCM - Lamy hybrid would be a better analogy: I don\u2019t think the Moreau wines have as much flesh and texture out of the gates as contemporary Ramonet. That said, Moreau\u2019s winemaking seems to have really dialed in to where it is today around 06/07/08; whereas Lamy and Pierre-Yves Colin have both evolved quite a bit over the last decade, within the parameters of their favored aesthetics, so perhaps we should be making the comparison in the other direction. John Gilman sometimes compares the Moreau wines today to Ramonet in the old days, and while I am too young to have tasted those wines on release, it makes some kind of sense in terms of their acid structure. Moreau, however, do achieve that sort of wheat toast / subtle praline patina (often conflated with \u201creduction\u201d), combined with citrusy fruit tones, that seems to be related to a number of harvest/winemaking choices including long \u00e9levage in a particular sort of barrel; and when pouring the wines blind to friends I have seen people identify them as Coche, I think for that reason.</p>",
        "post_number": 11,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 11,
